cff-version: 1.2.0
message: >
  If you use pty-speak in research, products, services, or accessibility
  work, please cite it as below. The author also welcomes — but does
  not require — a brief written acknowledgment when requested, to help
  demonstrate the impact and adoption of accessibility-first developer
  tooling. See the LICENSE file for the legal MIT terms and the
  separate non-binding acknowledgment request.
title: pty-speak
abstract: >
  A screen-reader-native Windows terminal, built in F# / .NET 9 / WPF,
  designed from the ground up for blind developers using NVDA, JAWS,
  or Narrator — with Anthropic's Claude Code (and other Ink/React
  TUIs) as the primary target workload. Parses ANSI into a typed
  event stream, derives semantic events from those, and exposes them
  through a real UI Automation Document role + Text pattern + UIA
  notification surface, so that what reaches a screen reader is
  structured semantics rather than diffed visible text.
